TITLE: The Fed would be 'flying blind' on interest rate decisions after a government shutdown
SUMMARY: A looming government shutdown could prevent the Federal Reserve from raising rates in November, Bank of America says.

TITLE: Striking unions impacting the economy at a level not seen in decades
SUMMARY: So far, the UAW stoppage has impacted just a small portion of the workforce with limited implications for the broader economy.

TITLE: August wholesale inflation rises 0.7%, hotter than expected, but core prices in check
SUMMARY: The producer price index was expected to increase 0.4% in August, according to the Dow Jones consensus estimate.

TITLE: Shipping giant Maersk unveils world's first vessel using green methanol
SUMMARY: The new container ship has two engines: one moved by traditional fuels and another run with green methanol.

TITLE: August core inflation, excluding food and energy, rose 0.3%, hotter than expected
SUMMARY: The consumer price index was expected to increase 0.6% in August and 3.6% from a year ago, according to the Dow Jones consensus estimate.

TITLE: Fears over access to credit hit highest level in more than a decade, New York Fed survey shows
SUMMARY: Respondents indicating that the ability to get credit is harder now than it was a year ago rose to nearly 60%.

TITLE: Taylor Swift is single-handedly giving a boost to hotel industry revenue
SUMMARY: An analysis found hotels in states Swift visited did notably better than the national average.

TITLE: 'Very stupid': Italy's bank tax remains controversial as government scrambles to update it
SUMMARY: Italy's shock tax on banks continues to prove controversial, even as the government insists it can "improve" it.

TITLE: Black unemployment rate declines in August, even as it rose across the board
SUMMARY: The jobless rate ran higher overall but slid for Black workers.

TITLE: Here's where the jobs are for August 2023 — in one chart
SUMMARY: Health care and social assistance was again the top area for job growth in August.

TITLE: Unemployment rate unexpectedly rose to 3.8% in August as payrolls increased by 187,000
SUMMARY: Nonfarm payrolls were expected to increase 170,000 in August, according to a Dow Jones consensus estimate.

TITLE: Taylor Swift, Beyoncé and 'Barbenheimer' are lifting consumer spending this quarter. But Morgan Stanley says it may not last
SUMMARY: Morgan Stanley sees a potential unwinding from these events, as well as the resumption of student loan payments, in the fourth quarter.

TITLE: U.S. job growth slowed sharply to 177,000 in August, below expectations, ADP says
SUMMARY: Economists surveyed by Dow Jones were expecting 200,000 jobs added in August.

TITLE: American workers are demanding almost $80,000 a year to take a new job
SUMMARY: The average "reservation wage," or the minimum acceptable salary offer to switch jobs, rose to $78,645 during the second quarter of 2023.

TITLE: China's economic model is 'washed up on the beach,' says veteran investor David Roche
SUMMARY: China's economic model is "washed up on the beach" and "not going to take off again," which will have a big impact on global markets, says veteran investor David Roche.

TITLE: Retail sales increased 0.7% in July, better than expected as consumer spending is holding up
SUMMARY: The advanced retail sales report showed a seasonally adjusted increase of 0.7% for the month, better than the 0.4% Dow Jones estimate

TITLE: Russian ruble slumps to near 17-month low, briefly moves past 100 against dollar
SUMMARY: Friday figures showed Russia's GDP expanded by a yearly 4.9% in the second quarter.

TITLE: Wholesale prices rose 0.3% in July, higher than expected
SUMMARY: The producer price index rose 0.3% for the month, slightly higher than expectations.

TITLE: July CPI report shows inflation gauge rose 3.2%, less than expected
SUMMARY: The consumer price index in July was expected to rise 0.2% from the prior month and 3.3% from a year ago, according to Dow Jones.

TITLE: Interest rates should stay around 5% for longer — even as inflation falls, top economist Jim O'Neill says
SUMMARY: Veteran economist Jim O'Neill says central banks will need to keep interest rates up around 5% across major economies for longer than the market expects, even as inflation subsides.

TITLE: Thursday's inflation data may be low, but don't expect the Fed to declare 'mission accomplished' yet
SUMMARY: History has shown that inflation is stubborn and can last longer than expected.

TITLE: Credit card balances jumped in the second quarter and are above $1 trillion for the first time
SUMMARY: Credit card debt 30 or more days late rose to 7.2% in the second quarter, up from 6.5% in Q1 and the highest rate since the first quarter of 2012.

TITLE: JPMorgan backs off recession call even with 'very elevated' risks
SUMMARY: Economists at the country's largest bank bailed on their recession call, joining a growing chorus that now thinks a contraction is no longer inevitable.

TITLE: The story of inflation, as told through your child's backpack
SUMMARY: Americans are expected to spend a record amount on school supplies this year. They're feeling sticker shock as inflation continues to push up prices.

TITLE: Black unemployment rate ticks lower in July as jobs market remains tight
SUMMARY: The jobless rate for Black workers fell to 5.8% in July, Labor Department data showed Friday.

TITLE: Here's where the jobs are for July 2023 — in one chart
SUMMARY: The health care and social assistance category grew by 87,100 jobs last month, continuing a hot streak.

TITLE: July jobs report: U.S. payroll growth totaled 187,000, lower than expected
SUMMARY: Nonfarm payrolls were expected to increase by 200,000 in July, according to the Dow Jones consensus estimate.

TITLE: Here's everything you need to look for in Friday's July jobs report
SUMMARY: Wall Street expects that nonfarm payrolls increased by 200,000 in July, the smallest gain since December 2020

TITLE: The Fitch U.S. ratings cut is here to stay, says analyst who worked on the S&P downgrade in 2011
SUMMARY: "It does not take a grand sovereign and analytics genius to understand that the fiscal profile of the U.S. is much worse than it has been," said Elliot Hentov.

TITLE: The Fitch analyst behind the U.S. downgrade breaks down the decision—and how the country can regain the top rating
SUMMARY: Fitch Ratings' Richard Francis told CNBC that the rating agency would need to see a long-term fiscal solution and a reduction of its debt.
